summary: He knows that Arya and Gendry were in love with him long before they even realized it.  It started one day, trying to traverse...
body:
He knows that Arya and Gendry were in love with him long before they even realized it. 

It started one day, trying to traverse up the slippery stairs of Winterfell. The soles of his boots were worn-out and ragged, and he had meant to get them replaced. After all, he wouldn’t want to go down in history being the fool who tripped and fell because his boots were not maintained.

“What’s wrong?” Arya had mocked, her grey eyes lit up with humor. “The all-powerful Targaryen prince can’t even climb the stairs without needing help?”

Gendry didn’t say anything, but he didn’t bother hiding the smirk dancing on his lips either. 

These two were the most insolent pair he has ever met. And he loved them for it. 

“Quiet.” He scowled back, trying to retain his dignity. As if the gods were taunting him and out to ruin his life, he felt his right boot slipped slightly under the icy edge. 

“Careful!” Arya yelped.

Gendry was quicker to react, standing right beside him. It wasn’t a terrible or noticeable mishap, and if Arya hadn’t shouted like that, no one would have even noticed it. But Arya’s yell had alerted Daenerys, who turned around in confusion. 

“I think,” Gendry’s voice was quiet, laced with amusement. “That our prince may require some help.”

Arya had let out a loud sigh, but the smile on her face was not of annoyance but of indulgence. “Oh, alright. Come on then, Aegon.”

As if the gods were trying to ruin his life further, they both extended their hands out towards him at the same time. He stared at their hands, and then at their faces. 

“Well?” Gendry prodded. 

Daenerys’ brow was climbing up to her hairline, and he was thankful that Jon was not present at least. 

He slipped his hands in theirs, feeling his heart beat rapidly in his chest. Even through the gloves, their hands were so warm. 

He hated how unaffected the both of them were. He hated how they damned propriety, never shy with their touches and affection. He hated how they would stare at him, as if he hung the stars in the night sky, and then enclosed each other in a bubble of their own, with no way in for anyone but themselves. He hated how he couldn’t even muster up the slightest hint of anger for that, because they both loved each other so much, and he’s already content with the way they looked at him.

body:
GoT Season 8

Not gonna lie, season 8 is probably gonna be a plot shit show after the writing in season 7. I mean everything was rushed, things stated in one episode were immediately forgotten or contradicted in the next and I just still seethe with the bullshit of having Arya and Sansa squabble.

Don’t even get me started with the whole Tyrion and Daenerys back and forth about the death sentence after she wins the battle with the Lannisters, like, seriously? Why did they have him argue? Was it death by fire that made him apprehensive or the fact it was a “great house” or just because these are people from his homeland.

Because he seemed perfectly fine at the end of season 6 to take control of the meeting with the masters and watch them die so I’m just gonna blame that on the writers.

Just don’t get your hopes up for the same storytelling quality in previous seasons. The only thing I’m sticking around for is the appearance of Drogon and Rhaegal, the battles and to see who wins or dies at the conclusion.

summary: Now that you're blog is back to normal, I'm back to harass you for your predictions/theories. I'm not confident in any reunion...
question: Now that you're blog is back to normal, I'm back to harass you for your predictions/theories. I'm not confident in any reunion except 1: Arya and Melisandre. I think that's a safe bet they run into each other again based on Mel's prophecy in season 3. How do you think it goes and under what circumstances do you think they meet?
answer:
Every time a character says “We will meet again” in Game of Thrones - you sure as fuck know they will follow through! (Each character should employ this line at the end of every conversation, amirite?) Anyway. I definitely think Arya will encounter Melisandre again. I’m not quite sure under what circumstances.

Melisandre, of course, foreshadowed her own death:

She’s done for! I’m not sure it will be by Arya’s hand, though. There’s a marvelous theory by GrayArea about Dany’s “fires” and “treasons” as foretold in the books. Basically, she argues that these are not treasons against Daenerys, but ones that she commits - and that Jon will fall in battle and be resurrected “against his will” (“If I fall, don’t bring me back”) by Dany’s orders - likely from a combination of Beric and Melisandre. I’d personally like to see something similar like with Mirri Maz Durr/Shireen… a blaze of glory. Dany’s “fire for love”.

And sorry but I gotta talk a little about Beric Dondarrion. Did he die at the Wall? Of course not! How can I be sure? Because he fucking told Sandor “We will meet again”. And in GoT, that’s basically a guarantee! But why bring this actor back? What purpose did Beric serve in the books? That’s two-fold. First, he shows us someone can come back from the dead multiple times. Second, he gives his “last kiss” to Catelyn to bring her back from the dead (in the books), yet he has yet to use this power on the show.

Speaking of Beric, he sort of foreshadows Jon’s death, too:

“You and I won’t find much joy while we’re here, but we can keep others alive.”

Qhorin Halfhand eerily says to Jon:

“Your death will be a gift to them in the south”

And many thanks to Sansa, for implying Jon would die upon seeing Arya again:

“When Jon sees you again, his heart will stop.”

(Really? Couldn’t have worded that shit ANY other way?)

But then, also thanks are in order for Jon… for implying Arya would die in AGoT:

“When the spring thaw comes, they will find your body with a needle still locked tight between your frozen fingers.”

Anyway, this ask wasn’t about Jon dying and coming back (lol) It was about Arya and Melisandre. And of course, there’s a chance Arya could be the one to kill Melisandre, of course.

“I see a darkness in you. And in that darkness, eyes staring back at me. Brown eyes, blue eyes, green eyes. Eyes you’ll shut forever.”

(Of course, Melisandre has red eyes in the books, but this is a show-only scene anyway, and she’s got blue eyes in the show. Also, what happens to Gendry on the show happens to Edric Storm in the books so Arya doesn’t have a beef with Mel, which also leads me to believe that she won’t be the one to kill her in the show, either. And being a trained assassin, Arya has probably shut all sorts of eyes for good, eh?)

Melisandre’s name (or “The Red Woman”) has fallen off of Arya’s list, too. And if she didn’t actually kill Gendry, then perhaps Arya won’t be out for blood (then again she did kill a child who was Gendry’s kin… so I’d personally love to see it, lol. Meryn Trant’s death is one of my favorite scenes in the show, no joke.)

My prediction is that Arya will say some scathing remarks about Melisandre, and let her know exactly how she feels about her and what she does - but that she’ll let Melisandre live, so long as she proves useful in some way.

And many thanks to Sansa, for implying Jon would die upon seeing Arya again:

“When Jon sees you again, his heart will stop.”

(Really? Couldn’t have worded that shit ANY other way?)

But then, also thanks are in order for Jon… for implying Arya would die in AGoT:

“When the spring thaw comes, they will find your body with a needle still locked tight between your frozen fingers.”

Anyway, this ask wasn’t about Jon dying and coming back (lol) It was about Arya and Melisandre. And of course, there’s a chance Arya could be the one to kill Melisandre, of course.

“I see a darkness in you. And in that darkness, eyes staring back at me. Brown eyes, blue eyes, green eyes. Eyes you’ll shut forever.”

(Of course, Melisandre has red eyes in the books, but this is a show-only scene anyway, and she’s got blue eyes in the show. Also, what happens to Gendry on the show happens to Edric Storm in the books so Arya doesn’t have a beef with Mel, which also leads me to believe that she won’t be the one to kill her in the show, either. And being a trained assassin, Arya has probably shut all sorts of eyes for good, eh?)

Melisandre’s name (or “The Red Woman”) has fallen off of Arya’s list, too. And if she didn’t actually kill Gendry, then perhaps Arya won’t be out for blood (then again she did kill a child who was Gendry’s kin… so I’d personally love to see it, lol. Meryn Trant’s death is one of my favorite scenes in the show, no joke.)

My prediction is that Arya will say some scathing remarks about Melisandre, and let her know exactly how she feels about her and what she does - but that she’ll let Melisandre live, so long as she proves useful in some way.

Every time a character says “We will meet again” in Game of Thrones - you sure as fuck know they will follow through! (Each character should employ this line at the end of every conversation, amirite?) Anyway. I definitely think Arya will encounter Melisandre again. I’m not quite sure under what circumstances.

Melisandre, of course, foreshadowed her own death:

She’s done for! I’m not sure it will be by Arya’s hand, though. There’s a marvelous theory by GrayArea about Dany’s “fires” and “treasons” as foretold in the books. Basically, she argues that these are not treasons against Daenerys, but ones that she commits - and that Jon will fall in battle and be resurrected “against his will” (“If I fall, don’t bring me back”) by Dany’s orders - likely from a combination of Beric and Melisandre. I’d personally like to see something similar like with Mirri Maz Durr/Shireen… a blaze of glory. Dany’s “fire for love”.

And sorry but I gotta talk a little about Beric Dondarrion. Did he die at the Wall? Of course not! How can I be sure? Because he fucking told Sandor “We will meet again”. And in GoT, that’s basically a guarantee! But why bring this actor back? What purpose did Beric serve in the books? That’s two-fold. First, he shows us someone can come back from the dead multiple times. Second, he gives his “last kiss” to Catelyn to bring her back from the dead (in the books), yet he has yet to use this power on the show.

summary:
"I'm not a squirrel," she said. 

“I’ll almost be a woman soon. I’ll be one-and-ten.”

  tbh i love arya asserting her girlhood...
body:
“I’m not a squirrel,” she said. “I’ll almost be a woman soon. I’ll be one-and-ten.”

tbh i love arya asserting her girlhood here. she’s had it violently taken from her and had to live as a boy for survival (and she was always treated by society as being a “bad” kind of girl) but despite that arya sees herself growing into a woman.
